2. Word Frequency

  1. Convert the description to tokens, remove all the stop words. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 20th century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words.
df %>% unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% filter(century == "20") %>% count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% head(10) %>% ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) + geom_col() + labs(y = '', x = 'Frequency')

  1. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 21st century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words. Plot a side-by-side bar charts to compare the most frequent words by the two centuries.
df %>% unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% filter(century == "21") %>% count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% head(10) %>% ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) + geom_col() + labs(y= '', x = 'Frequency')

df %>% unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% group_by(century) %>% slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% ungroup() %>% mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = century)) %>% ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = century)) + geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) + facet_wrap(~century, scales = "free") + labs(x = "Frequency", y = NULL) + scale_y_reordered()

4. Sentiment Analysis

  1. Is movies/TV Shows in the 21st century tends to be more positive than those in 20th century? Use the sentiment analysis by Bing lexicons to address the question.
library(tidyverse)
library(tidytext)
library(knitr)
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

  1. Do sentiment analysis using nrc and afinn lexicons. Give your comments on the results.
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(sentiment, n, fill=century))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>%
    mutate(sentiment = value) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=factor(sentiment)))+geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', fill = 'Sentiment', x = '')

5. Modeling

  1. Use the description to predict if a movie/TV show is in 20th or 21st century. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table.
library(caret)
library(themis)
## Warning: package 'themis' was built under R version 4.1.2
library(textrecipes)
## Warning: package 'textrecipes' was built under R version 4.1.2
# Select data and set target 
df1 <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = century) %>% 
  select(target, description) 
# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df1) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 10) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df1 <- juice(a)
# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df1$target, p = .2, list = FALSE)
df_train <- df1[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df1[-splitIndex,]
knn <- train(target~., data=df_train, method = "knn")
pred <- predict(knn, df_test)
cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.7385009
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
## Warning: package 'yardstick' was built under R version 4.1.2
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

  1. Create variable century2 taking three following values. (Hint: You can use the case_when function to do this)
- `21` if released_year is greater or equal to 2000

- `second_half_20`if released_year is greater than or equal to 1950 and less than 2000

- `first_half_20` otherwise
df$century2 = ifelse(df$release_year >= 2000, "21", ifelse(df$release_year >=1950,"second_half_20", "first_half_20"))

Predict century2 using the descriptions. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. (Notice that the codes for 8 should still work for this question)

library(caret)
library(themis)
library(textrecipes)
df2 <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = century2) %>% 
  select(target, description)
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df2) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 10) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df2 <- juice(a)
# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df2$target, p = .7, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df2[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df2[-splitIndex,]
knn2 <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "knn")
pred <- predict(knn2, df_test)
cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.8764198
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

6. Create another categorical variable from the data and do the following

df$type1 <- case_when(df$type =='TV Show' ~ 'TV', df$type =='Movie' ~ 'Movie')
- Plot side-by-side word frequency by different categories of the newly created variable
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(type1, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(type1) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = type1)) %>%

- Do sentiment analysis to compare different categories of the newly created variable

    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(type1, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(type1) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(type1) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(type1, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+

- Predict the newly created variable using the description. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. 
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = type1) %>% 
  select(target, description)
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 5) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df <- juice(a)
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df$target, p = .1, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df[-splitIndex,]
forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)
cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.5736722
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

df1 <- read_tsv('user_reviews.txt')

df1$rating <- case_when(df1$grade>7 ~ 'good', df1$grade<=7 ~ 'bad')

df1 <- read_tsv('user_reviews.txt')
df1$rating <- case_when(df1$grade>7 ~ 'good', df1$grade<=7 ~ 'bad')
df1 <- df1 %>% 
  mutate(target = rating) %>% 
  select(target, text)
a <- recipe(target~text,
       data = df1) %>% 
  step_tokenize(text) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(text, max_tokens = 5) %>% 
  step_tfidf(text) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df1 <- juice(a)
set.seed(2021)
splitIndex1 <- createDataPartition(df1$target, p = .7, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df1_train <- df1[ splitIndex1,]
df1_test <- df1[-splitIndex1,]
forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df1_train, 
                        method = "ranger")
pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df1_test)
cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df1_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.6570175
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df1_test$target)
library(yardstick)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot
